Date:  29/7/1846
Source:  Sketches in NZ
Author:  POWER
Vol / Page:  4
Edition:
Quote:   ... a few half-drunken loafers (beach-combers, as they are called here [in Auckland]) hanging about the numerous pot-houses. <i>Ibid.</i> 1849 Dec 9 (1958 ed. ) 117 Funds are running out and the evil consequences of employing beach-combers, escaped convicts and sailors [in pre-settlement Canterbury] are becoming every day more apparent. <i>Ibid.</i> 1850 Feb 17,  131 ... Lyttelton .... by all accounts is the receptacle of loose beachcombers and escaped lags and convicts, who have been employed in preference to honest and able men from the settlements.
